introduction.p:
So if f maps x to y, then f^{-1} maps y back to x. That is f^{-1} undoes f. Because of this we have


  f^{-1}( f(x) ) &= x  &\mbox{ for any $x \in A$}

   f( f^{-1}(y) )&=y &\mbox{ for any $y \in B$}


We have to be careful not to confuse f^{-1}(x) with \ds \frac{1}{f(x)}. The -1 is not an exponent.

example.p:
Let g(x) = \sqrt{x-1} on the domain x \geq 1. We can find the inverse in the same way:


  y &= \sqrt{x-1}

  y^2 &= x-1

  x &= y^2+1 = f^{-1}(y) & \text{or, writing input variable as ``$x$'':}

  f^{-1}(x) &= x^2+1.
